observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor adopt the minimum requirements of the laws and pertinent accounting and reporting guidelines, particularly applicable to cash donations received by the Municipality for DRRM operations with the following courses of actions, to wit:

a.	Require the Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO) to issue official receipt to all cash donations for DRRM operations that will be received by the municipality, deposit the same in the authorized government bank, and prepare a separate Report on Collections and Deposit (RCD);

b.	Require the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) to record the receipt and utilization of cash donations in the books of the municipality and prepare and maintain separate subsidiary ledger (SL) for "Trust Liabilities-DRRMF”;

c.	Require the Municipal Budget Office to prepare the Registry of Cash Donations and Utilization (RCDU) based on the RCD, Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) and credit memo received from MTO and MAO. The RCDU shall be maintained per donor per purpose and updated regularly by the Budget Unit;

d.	Ensure that charges to or utilization of the fund shall be based on Cash Donation Utilization Request (CDUR) and payment shall be made through the issuance of commercial check based on duly approved Disbursement Vouchers; and,

e.	Require the MDRRM Office to prepare and submit to NDRRMC through the Office of the Civil Defense (OCD), on the 5th day following the end of each month, the Report on the Receipt and Utilization of Cash Donations and copy furnished the respective COA Auditor.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Health Office, the Human Resource Management Office, and other concerned offices to submit the following documents:
The list of public health workers, including Barangay Health Workers, determined and approved by the Local Health Board;
Specific authority from the head of the agency to the claimants to physically report and to respond to the public health emergency during the state of national emergency indicating therein the assigned work stations/health facilities for COVID-19, the prescribed official working hours, and their duties and responsibilities;
Daily Time Records showing the actual date and time of the services rendered by the claimants as certified by the head of hospital, laboratory, or medical and quarantine facility, or his/her authorized representative;
Certification attesting to the truthfulness of the contents of the report and adequate consent for sharing of data obtained from the personnel involved. The certification must be signed by the head of human resource or personnel division and the head of the health facility, clearly indicating his/her designation or position; and,
Accomplishment Reports showing that the claimants have provided direct treatment and support care to COVID-19 patients.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following course of actions:

Require the Municipal Health Office to furnish the Municipal Accounting Office certified copies of the Property Transfer Reports (PTR) of all vaccines, drugs and medicines, medical and other supplies, and medical equipment received from the DOH-DCHD;

b.	Require also the Rural Health Unit (RHU) to submit a Summary Report of the Issuance/Distribution of vaccines, drugs and medicines, medical and other supplies in CY2020 and showing the inventories at hand as of December 31, 2020;

c.	Require the General Services Office to issue of Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE) and record the equipment received by the RHU;

d.	Require the Municipal Accounting Office to record in the specific Inventories accounts the cost of inventories at hand as of December 31, 2020, if any, and record in the specific Property, plant and equipment accounts the cost and the depreciation of the equipment; and,

e.	Establish specific policy guidelines for the receipt of properties through donations or any kind of transfer without cost to ensure proper reporting, accounting and monitoring thereof.

